But\nI. is \"beur policj\" was not intended to\nhart Westinghouse. Nor was it intend\nI to hit any of those trust companies\ni inks, rtal ebtale companies, or other\n.iterprieea in which the numerous\nl.oosevelts are interested. It looks, in\ni? ed, as if his bear policy had been\niiued exclusively agaiust independent\nr iustrial cuter prises which wero lit rug\ng off with the truats. I'he indepen\nii its have been crippled by it, and\nhi. e largely succumbed to the pressure\nbr. aght to bear by the MorguL-Koose\nw tic&ncial interests. And since this\nliicthsi been attained, the president j\ni< silo t>; satisfied.\nwill t?osr lorn bull for a while. He\nE ii CAise friend* of ali .those whom he\ni??- pretended to despise, ilio tnale\nf.c ors of all wealth, the criminal rich,\nthe undesirable citizen?, etc will be\nforgiven, end will enter tho kitchen\ncjtln&et. They have made millions out\nof tliis panic. Iliey have gained the uso\nof governmeet funds amounting to\nfill' ,000,000, while money wiw bringing\nfrom 30 to 00 per cent interest. l'liey\nhave crushed their competitors. They\nhave won great victories, and aru mnv\n\"gre.-.t capUiu.s of industry,\" again as\nt'it y were in 190-1. They may be relied\nupon to pile up a larger corruption\nfund uext year than they did three yoars\nn.:o.\n11)3 only unfortunate incident of this\nglori ;ua work of KooaeveU is, that some\nbody has been hit whom it was not\ninteii led to hit Hut this is of little\nconst luence so long as the good Steel\nTrus: has profited, ai?o the (.resident,\nand i is uncles, his brothers, sisters,\ncous ..a and aunts have not been hurt.\nIf anybody complains, the president\nconst him by exclaiming: \".My! 1\ndidn't mean to hit >on.\" And that\napology i allelic-* the poor wreck of a\ngrun.i, lor.? Exchange.\nPROTECTION AND PANIC.\nEvery disastrous panic which has oc\nctirrtd in this country culminated under\na rrp blicnn high tnritT law.\nThe recent experience in Njw York\nand lMlsbtirfr, the closing of bunks d<\nprcciii o'i of securities, thousands of\nbtiHinc e men ruined, other tbonsiitide\nitnalil to tlo business because of funds\nin banUi ami savings institutions tied up\nuntil j bile \"confidence is restored.\" was\nunderiiie Dingier tariff law, the sched\nules o< which are higher than those of\nany o'. or country and the highest over\nktioAD .ti tliiu country,\nA li lit money market is the excuse\ngiven for the laclt of funds with which\nto cotr. >ii business.\nAnd why is there a lack of money in\ncircu lut m? What has become of the\nmillion which are needed to carry on\nthe htiMiiesa of f he coiinir) t\nDurug the fiscal year ending Juno 30\nlast tlu revenues of this wondrously\nprosper .is country were f 00, 000,0 0 m\nexcess the extravagant and pt< lligite\nOJfperitli ires of the present federal\nati'iiinis ifion. Excess receipts over\nexpend)' :rr? thus far Mil* year makes\nup ii lot I of more than t Io0,00l>,'i0fl\nwitbdrnv. i from circulation and piled\nup in tin federal treasury when iMiould\nbo in tin pock?t* of the people fo eniihle\nthem to ;irry tin business.\nTho ex ;ess revenue under the high\nprotective tariff which tho republican\nparly has refused to re vino has in great\nmeasure ii used the tightness in the\nmoney market ami produced another\nrepublicnn panic.\nHut a few years ago the ooat of federal\ngovernment wua 91.50 per capita annu\nally. Today it is 812.00 per capita aud\nconstantly increasing. Not oonteot\nniLU unnecessarily burdening the people\nthrough extravagance ill administration,\nthis republican party sustains an unjust\nand inequitable tariff law which depletes\nthe people's pockets and pileB their\nmoney where they are unable to get\nat it.\nA few days ago the secretary of the\nreasury rushed to the scene of tinanciid\ndisaster and conferred u great benefit\nupon the people, llow? Dy lending\nthe tiuaucial institutions about one\nquarter of (he SlOO,tiO ','iOO which hue\nbeen taken from the people during the\npust fourteen mouth?.\nl'rotectiou aiui prosperity have been\nthe shibboleth of the republican part)\nI'lie real experience of the people under\nrepublican high protective lurid laws\nhas been protectioi and panic.\nThe commercial depression of lb7J-70\nwas ilue directly to the policies of the\nrepublican party.\nl'he crisis of 1893-U7 broke upon the\ncountry with the McKiutoy high tnriir\nlaw in full force and sevenUen months\nbefore tho euactmcnt of the Wilson\nbill.\nl'he recent bitter ex peri nee, with the\npeople's millions piled in the federal\ntreasury and rum mar og thousands of\nthem in the face, was under the LKngley\nturitl law, which the leaders of the\nrepublican party claim must uot be\nr< vised during the coiniug session of\ncongress.\nHereafter let the republican party be\nkuown as it really i>>, the party of proU c\ntion and panic.\nTHE EMANCIPATION OF NEVADA.\nThe govermeut has a thousand farms\nto sell ill Nevada, all of them with the\nwater laid on and ready foi irrigation.\nTho second unit of the Truckoe-Carson\nproject has been completed and the\nprice of the farms moderate. Tho home\nsteader can locate a hundred-acre farm\nfor 58, with the obligation to pay $2 an\naero annually for ten years. An irrigat\ned farm for $20 an acre is not expensive,\nl'he altitude is about 4/ CO feet, the\nclimate is mild aud the land fertile.\nThe goveruient bss already expended\nsome 000, OOO in the Carbon sink upon\ntho construction of nn elaborate system\nof canals and laterals to cover 200,000\nacres of land. All this means settle\nment and a large increase of population.\n1'ho great development of the eoutlern\nNevada mines provide* a ready market\nfor the farmers pro luce. Ultimately the\nproject will cover 11 0,000 acres and the\ncost of the whole system will be ?0,000,\n000.\nNevada is the first State to profit by\nthe federal irrigation enterprise. .New\ntowns are growing up in the irrigated\ndistrict. Three jear# ago the town of\nFallon had three houses. Already it has\na population of ^oine 1 ,*>u<i, with a high\nschool, hotel, churches and newspap) if.\nllie truth is that Nevada has just be\ngun to grow, l'he mines we all know\nabout, lint the agricultural potentialiti\nes of the State have attracted little at\ntention. No man is bo independent as the\nowner of an irriganed farm. The viciss\nitudes of tho seasons trouble him little.\nAll this means that Nevada is no\nlonger a pocket borrough, whose poli\ntics in a matter of bargain and sale to\nthe highest bidder, l'urtly by milling\ndevelopment and partly by the recla\nmation Novice Nevada is emancipated\nfrom the power of the sack.? Ogden\nStandard\nTHEY DON'T HOWL NOW.\n1'ho administration is preparing to\nissue ?50,0 JO, 1:00 of Panama bonds and\nS100,0c0,i;00 of interest bearing treasury\ncertificates for the purposo of relieving\ntlia present financial stringency. litis\nwill adil f 150,000, 00v to the interest\nbearing national debt, the interest on\nwhich must bo paid by tho people.\nThose bonds aud certificates are to bo\nused by National banks upon which to\nbase an increase ol circulation. Tho\nobject being to restore confidence by in\ncreasing tho circulating medium.\nIn iWHi, the party now in po*er claim\ned that the country hail more money\nthan it needed to carry on business and\nthat all that was needed was eonlldence\non the part of the people. Since then\nthe money supply in gold has inc tawed\nmuch faster than the population and it\nis hundreds of millions more no'v than\nit wiih then. In mlditiou to th ir>, the\nnoil baa folded bountiful harvests and\nprosperity has Messed the laud, liut\nstill there is the same ImJit of eonlldence\nin our monetary sjetetii now that the\ngold standard supporters claimed wan\ncaused by the threatened deluge of\n\"clieup money* that would follow\nClio free coinage of silver. l'he re\nis now no danger from that t-ource if,\nany over existed, and yet (lie people\nhave lost co oil deuce in (heir monetary\nsystem at a time w hen the country is\nenjoying unexampled prosperity of the\nrepublican brand.\nSlneo I8!l7, the republican parly has\nbeen in full possession of every branch\nof tho government. Kvery discovery of\ngold, tho sunshine, rain -tnd bounteous\nHarvests have been claimed as tin\ndirect results of republican policies, but\nwith all thin to (lie party's credit the\npeople have lost confidence again and a\npanic worse than that of IM'.'I is upoii\nthe country,\nI're/i lent Harris m's administration\nsmv the panic of IM'.I.I was sure to come\nand his secretary of the treasury prepar\ned flic (ilntes for an issuance of bonds\nto carry the country through the trou\nblous times abend. Ilofore flout bonds\nwore issued Cleveland's second ad minis\nt ration came in. The panic came as\nforeseen by Harrison and Cleveland is\nsued the bonds on the plates prepared\nby Harrison's secretary of the treasury.\nWhat a howl, then went up trooj repub\nlicans throats. A bond isbuo in the time\nof profound peace was an outrage upon\nthe people and sure evidence of demo\ncratic incompetency to manage the af\nfaire of the government.\nBut how times change! After being\nin undisturbed possession of the govern\nment sino3 1897, a period of rich gold\ndiscoveries and bounteous crops, tho\nrepublican party is issuing $150,000,000\nof interest-bearing indebtedness that\ntho people must pay to carry the coun\ntry through a panic that the wicked and\nincompetent democrats liad no hand in\nbringing about. If the panic of 181-3\nwas caused by democratic incompetence,\nwhat party is responsible for the pre\nsent panic?\nThe sun still eliiues the rain falls, the\nsoil produces Louiitifully. the wince\ncontinue to pour out their golden treas\nures, the Innd is free frc in pestilence\nind plague, for ail of which the repub\nlican party has claimed the credit. Hut\nuot withstanding a beuollcent Providence\nhas bUssed the country, tinimcial loss\naud ruin stare the people in the face\nthrough the destruction of coutidence,\nbrought about by republican misrule.\nIN MONOPOLY'S GRIP\nThe enormous value of competition as\na national asset is not generally under\ntit uo 1 But as to one of business, it\nmay be realized when wo consider care\nfully the following statement of the\nNew York Journal of Commerce:\n?The only force powerful enough to\ninduce the prompt adoption of improve\nments, and to inspire enterprise and\ningenuity, is competition.\"\nThis Biige Hnd indisputable proposition\nbos reference to railroad railmaking. It\nis a question, uot of economics merely,\nbut of life and death. Heiter rails must\nbe had. For the last tlscal year, 10,018\npersous were killed, 97,700 injured by\nreason of railroad accidents due mainly\nto defective rails produced by the tariff\nprotected Steel trust and its subsidiaries.\nThe economic results attending this\nwholesale slaughter havo never been\ncalculated. They are incalculable. And\nboth the slaughter and tho property and\nbusiness losses are duo to what? To\nthe parsimony aud greed of a tariff\nprotected monopoly 1'ho Journal of\nCommerce says:\n\"Subsidiary companies of the United\nStates Steel corporation have uad so\nnearly a monopoly of rail making as\npractically to control both the quality\nand the prices of the product for the\ncountry, and its vnst equipment dues\nuot seem to be adapted to i.u proving the\nquality without radical and costly\nchanges. In the last tew years the rail\nroads have been increasing tho capacity\nand the weight and the power of their\nrolling stock to handle tho growing\ntraflic with as much oconoiny as possi\nble, aud this has heeu putting a heavy\nstrain upon the tracks. At tho same\ntime the demand for new rails has been\nsuch as to stimulate the steel mills to\nrapid work to keep up with their orders,\nand this has not been favorable to care\nful manufacture. So many of tho multi\nplying accidents liuve been attributed\nto defective rails that tho rnirouds have\nbeen driven to insist upon an improved\ntype of rails and a better quality of steel\nin their production.\"\nRut how are wo to got better rails bo\nlong as monopoly, wo'ghed down with\nantiquated plants, controls the situa\ntion? And how can we expect improve\nments in other lines of production?\nTho .iMind-pattera ami their presidents\nwill have to answer for this shocking\nreactionary tendency of tariff laws.\nThoy will cry \"prosperity, prosperity!\"\nBut what is prosperity to the dead\nvictims of trust greed, o>* to the people\nat large who have no share in it?\nFRUIT OF REPUBLICAN POLICY.\nIn 1892, under a democratic adininis.\nt ration, the expenditures of tho federal\ngovernmnut amounted to 1 1 >,953,820,\nIn 1900, the expenditures Amounted to\n$730,717,582, an incre.iso of $3*20,703,759.\nTliii is an increase of more than 79 per\ncoot. Where it cost the taxpayers a\ndollar in 1892, it now coeta them $1.79\nto run the government. In 1892, tho\ntotal cost of tho federal government per\ncapita wao $0 39; while in 1900 it was\ni rr.oro than $8.75, an increase of more\nthan $2.30 per capita.\nThis en lulled an avorrgo increase of\nmore than $11. HU in the annual expenses\nof every family of live persons. But\nthis is not the worst. This extravagant\nincrease .if expenditure has noeeflsital\ntlie uiamntenanoe of of a tariff tux sys\ntem which has bred trusts liko vermin,\nand these trusts, having ii monopoly of\ntho home market, have raised prices\ntioro while lowering them abroad. So\nthat it costs every person, on an average\nS20 a year more tc live now than it did\nin 1892, exclusive of the $11.80 contribut\ned to public expenses; making $31,80\nper capita more now than in 1892; or\n$159 more for every family of tlvo per\nsona Fver since Doccmber, 1900, there\nha* boon, as ft result of this wretohed\npolicy a succession of spasms in Wall\nstreet. In that month, ar. J in January,\nFebruary, March, April, August, Sep\ntember and October, 1907, there have\nbeen reactionary movements. Practi\ncally wo liavo had a panic in tinance for\nII months, and the end is not yet. This\n.vrar-long panic lin* not been tho result\nof words spoken by Roosevelt, or Hearst\nor Delis. I*. lias not been the result of\nsocialistic agitation. It has resulted\nfrom wicked, dishonest, infamous leg\nislation on our statute books, put there\nby Republican congresses, and from the\nusurpation of the executive, aud of thc\njudges appointed by him to administer\nthese laws upon tbe principle that the\nend justifies the menus. Expenditures,\ntaxation, the extotione of the trusts, the\nusurpations of the president and the\ncourts are still iuoeeasiug and, therefore\ndiscontent is increasingr If the dis\ncontented will change tluir party aftilia\ntione, and elect a decent democrat to\nthe preeidecy, and decent democrats to\nthe national senate and house of repre\nsentatives, expenditures and taxation\nwill be decreased; the cost of living will\nbe decreased; the power of tho trust will\nbe destroyed, the evil work of the execu\ntive and the federal judges wll be\nbrought to book, and especially those\nwith limited incomes will tind their con\ndition improving, and generally times\nwill get better.\nROOSEVELT THE DESTROYER\nOF PROSPERITY.\nThat 'llioodore Roosevelt, President\nof tho United Stales, nud arch-dema\ngoguo of his time, is engaged iu a\nuefarious attempt to destroy the busi\nness prosperity of the nation is a fact\nwhich ia patent to all intelligent ob\nservers. That the recent financial panic\n?va b duo to his remorseless assaults on\nprivatu properly, every business uian\nwho can distinguish tlie workings of\ncause and elTect is already aware.\nTho count' y is informed daily by\ntho president's partis ins that Mr. R joso\nvelt is making uo attack ou private\nwealth, that liw activities are only\nemployed iti an attempt to s ninth tho\nwicked and predatory trusts, Mr.\nKooae veil himself sa\\stliat he is making\nno attack ou any legitimate business,\nthat bis policj threatens only the evil\ndoers, '.he remorseless and conscience\nless mag n ales who would di vert all the\nwealth of the nation, through illegal\nmeans, into tluir private purree.\nHow readily a he is often converted\ninto the semblance of truth! Mr. Uooic*\nvelt does manage to convey Uie impres\nsion l?y nitoULs of his hypuotic art that\nhe is a greater St. George, slaying a\ngreater dragon. H'Jt wher. on? turns to i\nthe col.) bare facts, what does be lin?l?\nHe tinds that Mr. Roosevelt is making\nwar on private capital only; that iu no\ninstanco has he ever tried to iujuro the\nreal predatory trusts of the nation.\nBvery trust that was doing buiness\nwhen Mr. Roosevelt became president is\ndoing business today. And meat of\ntheiu are doing a much larger buMuess\nnow than they were doing hen the late\nliininuled McKiulej's death made the\nnation's l.ig talker and small performer\ntbe p resilient of the nation. If Mr.\nRoosevelt really wanted to extract tho\nfangs of the trusts from the public llesh,\nhe would recommend the abolition of\ntho lanlT duties from all trust-made\nurtic.es. Thai he makes uo such rec\nommendation convicts him either of\nigtiorance or insincerity, aud he and his\nfriends can choose whichever horn of\nthe di en. ma that tio^t pleafli* ibeiu. It\nwill avail them not.\nMr. Roosevelt has not moved a lin\nger to remove one oppressive condition\nfrom which tho public suffers. Hut ho\nhas talked like a great, big, lubberly, .r\nreponsible sebjol l?oy, and ban destoryed\nconfidence in the minds of consovativo\nhussiucss me p. These see that we have\nin the president a man who for his own\ndemagogic purpose will uia'te rabti aud\nunfounded assertions concerning private\nwealth, and will recommend measures\nwhoso entire signill nuco lie* iu their\nsocialistic character. It is not asierted\ntbot Mr. Rouse velt is n socialist. It is\ndoubtful if be has tho mental caliber to\nuudorstand a writer who can reason as\nlogically from Ids, promisee, unsound as\nhis premises wore, as did Karl Marx.\nHul by con riant irresponsible preaching\noil tho evils of wedtli, nud making war,\nnot on the trust but oil privato property\nin the hands of certain individuals for\nwhom ho manifests an inherent dislike\nMr. Roosevelt precipitated Hie recent\nfinancial panic in the couutiv, and is ra\npidly unsettling Die business prosperity\nthe nation as a whole.? Kansas City\nPost.\nTHE INQU1STIVE DOY\n\"Pa, what is an 'asset currency\n\"An asset currency, eon, is a Swede.\"\n\"How do you make that out, pa?*\n\"Well, one day I asked I'. A. Peterson\nwhy Swede men changed their names\nfrom that of their father, aud after\nhearing his explanation, which lasted\nabout forty minutes, I didn't know any\nmore about it than I did before,\"\n\"What has that to do with the asset\ncurrency, pa?\"\n\"I asked a banker about the luinet\ncurrency, and after listening to his talk,\nmy thought returned to Peterson, and I\nconcluded tlmt it was the same thing.\"\n\"Are )oii h tlnancici, pa?\"\n\"No, sou, it keeps ine busy to p?> my\nbills and I usually lose the receipts booii\nafter.\"\n\"Well, pa, what do you know about\ntho present mono) stringency?\"\n\"I don't know anything about it,\nJamie, but I do know that in I '1)11 I wan\na liryan democrat one of those insuio\ndoinocrats, commonly called a traitor,\n?n amrehisl, an advo-nUi of a ftO-ceul\ndollar; I didn't know t r pretend to\nknow much about the ins and outs of\nthn question then before the people, but\nI put iny faith ill liryan and am glad of\nit, I hcliovod he war right thou and am\ncontl lent now il.at lie was right; that\nHio howl of '.\"ill-cent dollar' was an ex\npression ninnuficl tired by some fellow,\nand I don't know who he was and lime\nnever heard of him being discovered;\nho probably was one of tho fellows down\non Wall street that arc now begging (i.t\na obosp money.\nI'ho MK'cnt dollar men, thoio nine\ndemocrats and ever sime republicans\ntold us that wo had plenty of money to'\ntra