nfHE LAST MOMENTS\nVHEN THE SPIRIT CROSSES THE\nBORDERLAND.\n'asslng of a Life aa Seen by One\nWho la Not a Physician Death\nRattle a Shock to\nLlatenera.\nOno afternoon a reporter for the\nfew York Sun was Bitting in one of\nho rooms of the houso surgeon of a\nlospital Id New York city, smoking a\nIgnr and chatting v'th tho doctor\nvhlle the latter busied himself vith\nooklug over some Instruments that\nlo had taken from a case.\nAn orderly entered and said: \"Doc\nor, I tlilr.k ho Is dying now.\"\n\"Are his brother and mother here?\"\nisked tho house surgeon.\n\"No, they said they were coming,\nml they are not hero yot.\"\n\"It's a case of severe operation.\"\n>ahl the doctor to the reporter, \"lie\nook hlu ether nil right and rallied\n'roin tho shock, but he has been\noslng ground for two days. Will you\n:omo along with me?\"\nTho reporter folowcd tho physician\nnto ono of tho small rooms devoted\n:o private patients.\nLying llat on his back on the nar\nrow Iron cot was a young man, per\nliaps a little more than :t0. The bod\nNothing was In perfect order. Tho\nnarrow counterpane was spread\nsmoothly on the cot and folded over,\nwith the sheet across the patient's\nrhest.\nHis anna lay straight on either\nside. His face diii not indicate emaci\nation. His breathing was irregular,\nand there seemed to be a considerable\nInterval, sometimes longer and some\ntimes shorter, between the end of an\nuxplraUon and the beginning of an\nInspiration. The orderly stood at tho\nfoot of the cot.\n\"How long has he been uncon\nscious?\" the physician asked.\n\"A little more than an hour,\" re\npiled the orderly.\n\"Wo may talk.\" said tho doctor, \"ho\nwon't hear us.\" Uut this was s|>okcn\nIn a low tone, as befitted speaking in\nthe presence of death.\n\"iJoes every person die uncon\nscious he was asked.\n\"Many persons are conscious when\nthey believe the* uiu dying. They\nbecome unconscious, and they uiay\nnr may not regain consciousness arid\nlose it again before death takes plica\n\"A period of unconsciousness is I in\nmeasurable to the subject. A second,\na minute, a million years there is\nno difference so so far irs he in con\ncerned.\"\n\"Tho deatii rattle,\" whispered tho\norderly.\nTho Intermittent breathing of tho\nman on the cot had given way to a\nsound that was strange to one not ac\ncustomed to hour It? a Bound so far\nfrom human that It is made but once\nIn a lifetime, and that Is when one is\npassing to the other side of the bor\nderland of human existence.\n'Tnonrthly\" Is perhaps the one\nword that comes nea.^st to designat\ning this r.oimd I localise, maybe, of\nthe silence of the death chamber, It\nseems loud to ears not acquainted\nwith It. It seems even loud enough\nto be heard through the brick walls\nand out In the street.\n'I he sound ceases and the watchers\nturn their eyes toward the face of tho\nphysician. It begins again, as if tho\ndead were awakening.\n\"They will not come before ho\ndies,\" said the doctor.\n\"Is lie likely to regain conscious\nness, even for a moment?\" the phy\nsician was asked.\n\"I don't think so,\" was tho reply.\n\".May I bold his hand, so that If ho\ndoes be may feel that he Is not\nalone?\"\nThe physician nodded assent.\nTho man's linger tips seemed very\ncolli to tho warm hand that took them.\nThere was no sign of permission or\nresistance. Tho death rattle contin\nued with longer Intervals between\nthe breathings.\nKoi how many minutes this con\ntinued cannot lie told; It seemed an\nago. The strange, intent tlily sound\nceased, and two faces were turned\ntoward tli.it of the physician.\nThen there was a convulsive move\nment of til'- body on the cot, followed\nby a Jerk of tl:e head as If from\nstrangulation. The law of the patient\nfell and his eyes, which had opened,\nstared at tho wall.\n'I hero had been no sign of response\nfrom the hand of tho dying man.\nThe orderly stepped lo tho head of\nthe cot, and with the thumb and a lin\nger of ono hand pushed down Iho eye\nlids over